Spire Manchester Hospital's purpose-built site in Didsbury opened in 2017. The hospital has six theatres, including a hybrid theatre, an endoscopy suite, a five bedded critical care unit, two inpatient wards and in addition, there is a six bed dedicated paediatric suite and a day case ward.

 We treat NHS, insured and self-funding patients. For more information on the NHS e-Referral Service (e-RS) please visit the Departments and Services page.

 Key NHS treatments available at Spire Manchester Hospital

We offer NHS care for a number of clinical specialties including:

 - ENT

 - General surgery / colorectal surgery

  • Gallstones
  • Hernia

- Orthopaedic treatments for:

  • Foot and ankle
  • Hand and wrist
  • Hip
  • Knee
  • Shoulder

- Upper GI treatments including endoscopy

- Urology

- Vascular

Spire Manchester Hospital is guided by the formulary and decisions made by the Greater Manchester Medicines Management Board for the clinical indications that we are contracted to treat.

http://gmmmg.nhs.uk/html/formulary_bnf_chapters.html

Services.ServiceName: Mental health services for alcohol addiction

Metrics.ElementText:
Eclypse is a free and confidential service for young people aged 25 and under in Manchester. We provide support for anyone who is concerned about their own or somebody else’s drug or alcohol use. Our friendly team is on hand to provide advice and tailored support plans to help you achieve your goals. We’re a confidential service, which means we won’t inform anyone of your involvement with us, unless there was a risk of harm to yourself or somebody else. We work in a way that suits you – that might be having appointments over the phone, in-person at our base or your place of choosing, or online via Zoom. 

Eclypse provide access to treatment (drugs/alcohol) and offer holistic support to children, young people and families.  Support can include smoking cessation, sexual health advice, managing debt, stress and anxiety management, improving self-esteem and lots more. The Family Team work with children affected by parental substance misuse and their parents to promote resilience and family unity. We can also supported people concerned about a young person’s drug/alcohol use, as we understand the difficulties this can bring to people of any age. 

Eclypse will work with any young person living in the Manchester City Council borough, or going to school in the Manchester borough if they want to have appointments at school. There are similar services on offer in neighbouring areas of Salford, Trafford, Rochdale, Oldham and other Greater Manchester areas.

Eclypse also offer groupwork programmes and can deliver bespoke professional training. See our Eventbrite page for online training sessions we have coming up, which cover varied topics related to drugs, alcohol and young people in Manchester, aimed at professionals working within relevant areas.
Monday to Friday 9am - 5pm
Manchester

Accessing Eclypse’s support and advice is easy, and we accept both self and professional referrals. You can call or email using the contact details above, or fill in our short online referral form here - https://www.changegrowlive.org/manchester/referrals. We aim to get back to you within 48 hours.
Make sure to follow us on our socials! We’re @eclypsemanchester on Instagram and @ManchesterEclypse on Facebook!

The people at Home Instead South Manchester and North Trafford offer a flexible, personalised service with one simple aim – to provide the kind of care they’d want for their own families. To make this possible they do things differently.

They only recruit CareGivers with a genuine affinity for older people, then train them in the skills and ethos needed to deliver to it. Each client is matched with their own regular CareGiver so they can build the personal relationship vital to effective, dignified care.

Every client, or their family, agrees their own tailored package, providing the service they want, when they want it, and their own schedule so they always know who they’ll be seeing and when, and when needs change the service changes too. To some this might seem like the gold standard, but at Home Instead South Manchester and North Trafford, it’s just what every older person deserves.

Information supplied by homecare.co.uk

Metrics.ElementText:
The NHS Newborn Hearing Screening Programme (NHSP) offers all parents in England the opportunity to have their baby’s hearing screened shortly after birth.

It aims to identify hearing loss early in newborn babies. Early diagnosis enables earlier intervention and support leading to better outcomes for children.

A hearing screen is offered to all eligible babies under 3 months of age in England. The screen takes place either at the birth hospital, at an outpatient clinic or during a health visitor home visit.
You should be automatically offered a screen for your baby shortly after birth. If you have any concerns please contact your local screening service.

Services.ServiceDescription:
Audiology & Hearing Aid Department

Why might patients be referred to this department?

The audiology and hearing aid clinic is able to assess and manage patients who are complaining of hearing and/or balance difficulties.  We are able to offer quality care to patient suffering from conditions such as hearing loss, tinnitus and vertigo.

What will happen and who will you meet?

When you attend the department the nature of testing performed will be dictated by your problem.  It might be a simple ear examination or a full hearing and balance work up.  Any procedure you are asked to undertake will be fully explained beforehand and verbal consent will be requested.

Depending on your problem and diagnosis you will be assessed and treated by an appropriate member of the audiology team.  We have a large number of qualified members of staff specialising in the diagnosis and management of hearing loss, tinnitus and/or balance disorders.  We are part of a multidisciplinary team with access to ENT medical staff and further complex diagnosis.

If hearing aids are required we offer a range of high quality devices and individual rehabilitation which will be tailored to each patients’ specific needs.  We can maintain your hearing aids regularly and will update and review hearing prescriptions on a regular basis.

Where can you find these services?

The audiology department is based at North Manchester General Hospital in Out Patient B.  We also offer appointments at local health centres.  Please contact the department directly for more information.

When is the department open?

Appointments are available from 8.00 am to 6.00 pm Monday to Friday at North Manchester General Hospital and a number of community clinics. We also provide a service at North Manchester General Hospital only between 9.00 -1.30pm on Saturdays – by appointment only.

Welcome to Hawthorn Medical Centre. We are an NHS GP Surgery and Walk-in Centre in Levenshulme, Manchester.

Our walk-in service is open to all NHS patients for urgent, on-the-day care. We are open 7 days a week and only close on Bank Holidays. Please see the Surgery times below for walk-in services. The clinics are run on a first-come, first served basis so please telephone in advance towards the end of the session to check availability.

For registered patients the surgery employs regular GPs in order to meet the health needs of the local areas, The Surgery runs extensive clinics including child screening,  immunisation services and long term condition reviews.

We employ a Focussed Care worker who can help with advice on social care and benefits , onsite infant and parent services, a great team of nursing and back office staff to support our GPs.

Please call today on 0161 220 6080 or visit our website at http://www.hawthornmedicalcentre.org.uk for more information or to register as a new patient.

We look forward to hearing from you.

The Hawthorn Team.

value.SummaryText:
I am Dr Zammad Chishti. I am the Lead GP at Woodlands Medical Practice, Brooklands, Manchester. I am a member of Royal College of Physicians and also a member of Royal College of General Practitioners. As you all know, I took over the practice in April 2017 from my trainer, Dr Roger Ma-Fat and now I am the senior partner at the practice.

Mrs Lynn Cordock is our new practice manager. She has a vast experience in practice management and just in few months of starting, she has already made lots of healthy changes in the practice.

Firstly, on behalf of Woodlands Medical Practice, we would like to thank all our patients and staff who showed lots of patience with the changes that happened in the practice in the last year or so. I feel proud to inform that the building work at Woodlands Medical practice has been completed. Due to the increasing size of the patients list at the practice, we have created an extra consultation room downstairs which means that 2 doctors along with a Clinical pharmacist/Nurse can run clinic together on the ground floor at the same time.

We are a team of 2 x doctors, a practice manager, an office manager, a clinical pharmacist, a practice nurse and 4 receptionists.

 At our premises, we perform ultrasound scans every week carried out by our reputable ultrasound contractors. Ultrasounds are performed within 1-2 weeks of been requested and our patients don’t have to travel far for ultrasound scans.

We also perform Minor surgery procedures at our premises. Minor surgery is performed by our expert, Dr Faisal Bhutta. He also performs steroid joint injections. 

Can I also please remind that appointments should not be made for repeat prescriptions, request for Paracetamol/Ibuprofen or other prescriptions which are available over the counter for example creams for thrush, verrucas, nappy rash etc.

Pl visit https://www.nhs.uk/live-well/healthy-body/common-illnesses-your-pharmacist-can-help-with/Your local pharmacy can help you with the minor conditions.

We are a diverse , multilingual practice situated in the heart of greater Manchester providing a valuable service to the local community.

Working together to provide warm personalised care packages for our patients.

Services.ServiceDescription: You can make an appointment to see the practice nurse for asthma or COPD  review.We offer lung function test including peak flow and spirometry.Please bring any inhalers or medication with you when attending your appointment.

The practice nurse is happy to see babies who can not attend on friday on any day with a booked appointment, please ask the receptionist for further information.

If you or someone you are a carer for  has  been diagnosed  with learning dissabilities, you are advised to have a annual health review in which your condition and other aspects of your general health can be discussed.You can contact the surgery for an appointment.A care plan should be agreed with the GP, you should be given a copy of the agreed care plan to keep at home.Carers should be identified with names and contact details at the appointment.All care plans in place should be reviewed at least once a year if there are no changes before the period elapses. All patients on the register are entitled to seasonal flu vaccines.
We offer in house ECG, blood testing doppler and ambulatory blood pressure monitoring services for our patients as part of our one stop investigation service.

value.SummaryText:
Welcome to Surrey Lodge Group Practice.

The practice can trace its origins back over 100 years. There were originally two practices which amalgamated in 1969 with Drs Whittaker and Fowler joining Dr Bradfield in the practice on Birch Lane. This was the original Surrey Lodge building from which the present practice takes it name. The practice moved into Longsight Health Centre in 1977 and practised from there until it moved into its current premises on Anson Road in 1992. Since moving here we have developed and extended the building to provide more services to more patients.

Services.ServiceDescription: We hold a baby clinic every Tuesday afternoon from 12:00 until 14:00.  You can attend for childhood immunisations or general advice.  Please do not bring sick babies to this clinic, book an appointment to see a doctor or nurse.
We run a dedicated clinic to care for our patients with diabetes, including insulin therapy.

value.OrganisationName: Change Grow Live Drug And Alcohol Service – Manchester, Zion Centre

Services.ServiceName: Alcohol addiction - support for family and friends

Metrics.ElementText:
Change Grow Live Manchester work with anyone looking to make positive changes related to drug & alcohol use. We approach treatment with an open mind, free from judgement. If your goals don't include treatment and recovery, but you do want to reduce the harmful impacts of drug & alcohol use, we can help with this too.  

Change Grow Live are a national organisation, with the aim to help people change the direction of their lives, grow as individuals and live life to its full potential. In Manchester, we offer support with harm reduction, needle exchange, housing, criminal justice, employment, education & training and homeless outreach. We have links with other services, including a smoking addiction service also under the Change Grow Live umbrella, called Be Smoke Free, and we offer a service which works specifically with young people, called Eclypse. We work with Emerging Futures and Acorn to deliver our psychosocial intervention groups and after-treatment care, and LGBT Foundation to provide specialist support related to LGBTQ+ issues for those in treatment. 

Change Grow Live's teams work in partnership with service users to assess their requirements and to plan individual treatment plans and support that will help service users to address their problems and achieve their personal goals.

We provide a full range of treatment and recovery interventions for people who require services for their drug or alcohol use. We do this by providing:

- Initial assessment to work out what support will benefit you
- Brief interventions (including harm reduction advice and support over the phone)
- Medically assisted treatment (MAT)
- Support sessions with recovery coordinators and engagement workers – one-to-one and in small groups
- Second opinions when requested by a GP
- Community detox
- Referral for in-patient detox
- Links to rehab clinics
- Peer Support groups – informal drop-ins, and structured group programmes
- Health assessments
- Blood-borne virus (BBV) tests and treatment - HIV, Hep B and Hep C
- Hep B & Hep C vaccinations
- Needle Syringe Programmes (AKA needle exchange)

We also deliver free online training to professionals on topics related to drug & alcohol use, which you can find on our Eventbrite page:   https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/cc/adult-drug-alcohol-training-for-professionals-2132019
Monday to Friday, 9am – 5pm. Some evening openings available – please ring 0161 823 6306 for details
Central Manchester

We take referrals from any source as long as they’re with the person’s consent. Clients can also self refer to the service.

Please complete online referral form:  https://www.changegrowlive.org/manchester/referrals

value.SummaryText:
The practice is long established and was first located in Slade Hall, a quarter of a mile along Slade Lane from the present location.  The practice moved to West Point Medical Centre in 1968, and has been extensively redeveloped in recent years.  We are situated on a pleasant site in the Rushford Conservation Area, opposite West Point Park and on the corner of Slade Lane and Victoria Road.

We are strongly committed to providing high quality, modern and personal care for all of our patients.

West Point Medical Centre has long established relationships with both the University of Manchester and Health Education England, in delivering teaching for undergraduate Medical Students and providing postgraduate medical education.  As such, patients may be asked if they are happy, on occasions, to be consulted by undergraduate Medical Students, supervised by either Dr Askew or Dr Mehra, or by a suitably qualified GP in training, although patients wishes in respect teaching and training will be respected and adhered to at all times.
